OOB Fee & Royalty System — Design Specification
Overview
This document defines the fee and royalty architecture for the Open Order Book (OOB) protocol.

Fee model: A fixed ~1% total fee, split equally three ways between the protocol, the listing marketplace, and the buying marketplace.

Royalty model: Optional by default. If a listing marketplace chooses to enforce royalties, they are baked into the signed order and enforced by Seaport automatically. No zone or registry logic needed for royalties.

1. Fee Structure
Split
Recipient	BPS	Percentage	How
OOB Protocol	33	0.33%	Baked into order at listing time
Listing Marketplace	33	0.33%	Baked into order at listing time
Buying Marketplace	33	0.33%	Added as tip at fill time, enforced by Zone
Total	99	~1%	
NOTE

0.33% × 3 = 0.99%, not exactly 1%. This is because basis points are integers. Options:

Use 33 + 33 + 33 = 99 bps (0.99%) — clean and equal
Use 34 + 33 + 33 = 100 bps (1.00%) — protocol takes the extra bp
Make this configurable in the protocol config
Recommendation: 33 + 33 + 33 = 99 bps. Simple, equal, transparent.

Example: 1 ETH Listing
At listing time (baked into signed order):

#	Consideration item	Recipient	Amount
0	Seller proceeds	Seller	0.9934 ETH
1	Protocol fee	OOB Treasury	0.0033 ETH
2	Listing MP fee	Marketplace 1	0.0033 ETH
Total order price		1.0 ETH
At fill time (added by buying marketplace):

#	Extra consideration	Recipient	Amount
3	Buying MP tip	Marketplace 2	0.0033 ETH
Buyer pays total		1.0033 ETH
Same-marketplace scenario
When the listing and buying marketplace are the same entity:

Recipient	Amount	Note
Seller	0.9934 ETH	
OOB Protocol	0.0033 ETH	0.33%
Marketplace	0.0033 + 0.0033 = 0.0066 ETH	0.66% total (both shares)
Buyer pays	1.0033 ETH	Same as cross-marketplace
The marketplace tip goes to their own fee address, so they naturally collect both the listing and buying shares. No special logic needed.

Key property: Buyer pays the same everywhere
No matter which marketplace the buyer uses, they always pay listing price + 0.33%. There is no incentive to shop across marketplaces for lower fees.

2. Enforcement Mechanism
What's baked into the order (enforced by Seaport)
The protocol fee (0.33%) and listing marketplace fee (0.33%) are consideration items in the signed Seaport order. They are:

Signed by the seller via EIP-712 — tamper-proof
Enforced by Seaport at settlement — the transaction reverts if any consideration item isn't satisfied
Validated by the OOB API at submission time — orders without the protocol fee are rejected
These are already 100% secure. No zone needed.

What's added at fill time (enforced by Zone)
The buying marketplace fee (0.33%) is added as an extra consideration item via fulfillAdvancedOrder. This is the "tip" mechanism in Seaport.

Without a zone: tips are optional. A buyer could call Seaport directly and skip the tip.

With a zone: the tip becomes mandatory. The zone validates that the tip is present and sufficient.

Zone Contract
Why Zone is the best option
Option	100% bypass-proof?	Decentralized?	Complexity
Zone contract	✅ Yes	✅ Yes	Low (~60 lines)
Tips without zone	❌ No (anyone can skip)	✅	None
Signed zone (co-signature)	✅ Yes	❌ No (needs OOB API)	Medium
Contract orders	✅ Yes	✅ Yes	Very high
The Zone contract is the only option that is both 100% bypass-proof AND fully decentralized (no dependency on OOB API for fills).

How it works
All OOB orders use orderType: FULL_RESTRICTED (instead of FULL_OPEN)
The order's zone field points to the OOB Zone contract
The zoneHash encodes: originalConsiderationCount + minTipBps (33)
When anyone fills the order, Seaport calls zone.validateOrder()
The zone checks that extra consideration items total at least 0.33% of the order price
If the check fails, the entire transaction reverts
Zone contract (pseudocode)
solidity
contract OOBZone is IERC165 {
    function validateOrder(ZoneParameters calldata zoneParams)
        external view returns (bytes4)
    {
        // Decode parameters from zoneHash
        uint256 encoded = uint256(zoneParams.zoneHash);
        uint256 originalCount = (encoded >> 16) & 0xFF;
        uint256 minTipBps = encoded & 0xFFFF;  // 33 = 0.33%
        
        // Must have extra consideration items (the buying MP tip)
        require(
            zoneParams.consideration.length > originalCount,
            "Missing marketplace tip"
        );
        
        // Calculate total price from original consideration items
        uint256 originalPrice = 0;
        for (uint i = 0; i < originalCount; i++) {
            ItemType itemType = zoneParams.consideration[i].itemType;
            if (itemType == ItemType.NATIVE || itemType == ItemType.ERC20) {
                originalPrice += zoneParams.consideration[i].amount;
            }
        }
        
        // Calculate total tips (everything beyond original items)
        uint256 tipTotal = 0;
        for (uint i = originalCount; i < zoneParams.consideration.length; i++) {
            ItemType itemType = zoneParams.consideration[i].itemType;
            if (itemType == ItemType.NATIVE || itemType == ItemType.ERC20) {
                tipTotal += zoneParams.consideration[i].amount;
            }
        }
        
        // Enforce minimum tip
        uint256 minTip = (originalPrice * minTipBps) / 10000;
        require(tipTotal >= minTip, "Tip below minimum");
        
        return this.validateOrder.selector;
    }
    
    function supportsInterface(bytes4 interfaceId) external pure returns (bool) {
        return interfaceId == type(IERC165).interfaceId
            || interfaceId == 0x3839be19; // ZoneInterface
    }
}
What Seaport functions are covered?
Seaport function	Zone validated?	Can bypass?
fulfillOrder()	✅	❌ (can't add tips → zone rejects for missing tip)
fulfillAdvancedOrder()	✅	❌ (zone validates tip amount)
matchOrders()	✅	❌
matchAdvancedOrders()	✅	❌
fulfillAvailableOrders()	✅	❌
fulfillAvailableAdvancedOrders()	✅	❌
There is no Seaport function that bypasses zone validation for restricted orders.

3. Royalty System
Design principle
Royalties are optional by default. The listing marketplace decides. If they include royalties, Seaport enforces them automatically. No zone logic, no registry, no extra mechanisms needed.

How it works
Marketplace enforces royalties
typescript
const oob = new OpenOrderBook({
  chainId: 8453,
  enforceRoyalties: true,  // ← marketplace opts in
});
When 
createListing()
 is called, the SDK:

Calls supportsInterface(0x2a55205a) on the NFT contract (EIP-2981 check)
If supported: calls royaltyInfo(tokenId, priceWei) to get receiver + amount
Adds the royalty as a consideration item in the order
Seller signs → royalty is permanent, enforced by Seaport
Consideration items (royalty-enforcing marketplace):
  [0] Seller proceeds    → seller       (price - protocol - MP - royalty)
  [1] Protocol fee       → OOB          (0.33%)
  [2] Listing MP fee     → marketplace  (0.33%)
  [3] Creator royalty    → creator      (e.g., 5%)
Marketplace doesn't enforce royalties
typescript
const oob = new OpenOrderBook({
  chainId: 8453,
  // enforceRoyalties defaults to false
});
SDK does NOT auto-query EIP-2981. Marketplace can still manually provide royaltyBps and royaltyRecipient in 
CreateListingParams
 if they want, but it's optional.

Why this is already bypass-proof
Royalties are consideration items in the signed Seaport order. If they're included:

The seller signed them — can't be removed without invalidating the signature
Seaport enforces them — the fill transaction reverts if royalties aren't paid
No zone logic is needed — Seaport handles it natively
If they're NOT included (marketplace chose not to enforce):

No enforcement, no problem — that's the marketplace's choice
Buyers on any marketplace fill royalty-free — the system doesn't care
Example with royalties
1 ETH listing, 5% creator royalty, listing marketplace enforces:

Recipient	Amount	Source
Seller	0.9434 ETH	Price - all fees - royalty
OOB Protocol	0.0033 ETH	0.33% (baked in)
Listing MP	0.0033 ETH	0.33% (baked in)
Creator	0.05 ETH	5% royalty (baked in)
Buying MP	0.0033 ETH	0.33% (tip at fill)
Buyer pays	1.0033 ETH	
What the zoneHash encodes
When royalties are present, the originalConsiderationCount increases from 3 to 4:

zoneHash field	Without royalty	With royalty
originalConsiderationCount	3	4
minTipBps	33	33
The zone uses originalConsiderationCount to determine where original items end and extra items (tips) begin. This correctly handles both cases without any royalty-specific logic in the zone.

4. SDK Configuration
Marketplace config
typescript
const oob = new OpenOrderBook({
  // Required
  chainId: 8453,
  
  // Marketplace identity (fee collection)
  feeRecipient: '0xMarketplaceFeeAddress',
  
  // Royalty policy
  enforceRoyalties: true,  // default: false
  
  // Optional
  apiUrl: 'https://api.openorderbook.xyz',
  apiKey: 'mp1-key-xxx',
});
Creating a listing
typescript
const listing = await oob.createListing({
  collection: '0xNFT',
  tokenId: '42',
  priceWei: '1000000000000000000', // 1 ETH
  // royaltyBps and royaltyRecipient are auto-populated
  // from EIP-2981 if enforceRoyalties is true
});
Filling an order
typescript
// SDK always adds the 0.33% tip to the marketplace's feeRecipient
const txHash = await oob.fillOrder(orderHash);
// Buyer pays: listing price + 0.33% buying MP tip
Protocol config (from API)
json
{
  "protocolFeeBps": 33,
  "protocolFeeRecipient": "0xOOB_TREASURY",
  "minTipBps": 33,
  "zoneAddress": "0xOOB_ZONE"
}
The SDK fetches this from GET /v1/config and uses it to:

Add the protocol fee as a consideration item (33 bps to OOB treasury)
Set orderType: FULL_RESTRICTED and zone: zoneAddress
Encode minTipBps into zoneHash
